<hr />

<h3>Small Screen Table</h3>
<div class="row">
  <div class="col w-60">
    <div class="table-mobile">
      <table class="table-Stripe">
        <thead class="table-header">
          <tr>
            <th>TH Col Start</th>
            <th>Item 2</th>
            <th>Item 3</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tfoot class="table-footer">
          <tr>
            <th>TH Col End</th>
            <th>Item 2 End</th>
            <th>Item 3 End</th>
          </tr>
        </tfoot>
        <tbody class="table-body">
          <tr>
            <th>Title TH</th>
            <td>Data area 1 with more text</td>
            <td>Data area 2 with more text</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Title TH</th>
            <td>Data area 1</td>
            <td>Data area 2</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Title TH</th>
            <td>Data area 1</td>
            <td>Data area 2</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Title TH</th>
            <td>Data area 1</td>
            <td>Data area 2</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th>Title TH</th>
            <td>Data area 1</td>
            <td>Data area 2</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div> <!-- end .w-60 -->

  <div class="col w-40">
    <p>
      A simple means of viewing tabular data on a small screen.
    </p>
    <p>
      Enclose a table in a parent element with a class of <code>.table-mobile</code>
      to give the table a horizontal scroll when the screen becomes too small to
      view all of it's content.
    </p>
    <code class="tiny">
      &lt;div class="table-mobile"><br />
      &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;table>...&lt;/table><br />
      &lt;/div>
    </code>

    <p>
      For another take on small screen tables, check out the 
      <a href="https://github.com/bleachedgraphics/responsive-table-reborn" title="View on GitHub">revised Zurb's responsive table</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</div> <!-- end .row -->
</section> <!-- end .content -->
